11 Section 3. KRS 342.316 is amended to read as follows:
12 (1) (a) The employer liable for compensation for occupational disease shall be the
13 employer in whose employment the employee was last exposed to the hazard
14 of the occupational disease. During any period in which this section is
15 applicable to a coal mine, an operator who acquired it or substantially all of its
16 assets from a person who was its operator on and after January 1, 1973, shall
17 be liable for, and secure the payment of, the benefits which would have been
18 payable by the prior operator under this section with respect to miners
19 previously employed in the mine if it had not been acquired by such later
20 operator. At the same time, however, this subsection does not relieve the prior
21 operator of any liability under this section. Also, it does not affect whatever
22 rights the later operator might have against the prior operator.
23 (b) The time of the beginning of compensation payments shall be the date of the
24 employee's last injurious exposure to the cause of the disease, or the date of
25 actual disability, whichever is later.
26 (2) The procedure with respect to the giving of notice and determination of claims in
27 occupational disease cases and the compensation and medical benefits payable for
Page 8 of 17
SB004710.100 - 984 - XXXX 2/19/2026 11:42 AM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 47/GA
1 disability or death due to the disease shall be the same as in cases of accidental
2 injury or death under the general provisions of this chapter, except that notice of
3 claim shall be given to the employer as soon as practicable after the employee first
4 experiences a distinct manifestation of an occupational disease in the form of
5 symptoms reasonably sufficient to apprise the employee that he or she has
6 contracted the disease, or a diagnosis of the disease is first communicated to him or
7 her, whichever shall first occur.
8 (3) The procedure for filing occupational disease claims shall be as follows:
9 (a) The application for resolution of claim shall set forth the complete work
10 history of the employee with a concise description of injurious exposure to a
11 specific occupational disease, together with the name and addresses of the
12 employer or employers with the approximate dates of employment. The
13 application shall also include at least one (1) written medical report
14 supporting his or her claim. This medical report shall be made on the basis of
15 clinical or X-ray examination performed in accordance with accepted medical
16 standards and shall contain full and complete statements of all examinations
17 performed and the results thereof. The report shall be made by a duly-licensed
18 physician. The commissioner shall promulgate administrative regulations
19 which prescribe the format of the medical report required by this section and
20 the manner in which the report shall be completed.
21 1. For coal-related occupational pneumoconiosis claims, each clinical
22 examination shall include a chest X-ray interpretation by a National
23 Institute of Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) certified "B"
24 reader. The chest X-ray upon which the report is made shall be filed
25 with the application as well as spirometric tests when pulmonary
26 dysfunction is alleged.
27 2. For other compensable occupational pneumoconiosis claims, each
Page 9 of 17
SB004710.100 - 984 - XXXX 2/19/2026 11:42 AM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 47/GA
1 clinical examination shall include a chest X-ray examination and
2 appropriate pulmonary function tests.
3 (b) To be admissible, medical evidence offered in any proceeding under this
4 chapter for determining a claim for occupational pneumoconiosis resulting
5 from exposure to coal dust shall comply with accepted medical standards as
6 follows:
7 1. Chest X-rays shall be of acceptable quality with respect to exposure and
8 development and shall be indelibly labeled with the date of the X-ray
9 and the name and Social Security number of the claimant. Physicians'
10 reports of X-ray interpretations shall: identify the claimant by name and
11 Social Security number; include the date of the X-ray and the date of the
12 report; classify the X-ray interpretation using the latest ILO
13 Classification and be accompanied by a completed copy of the latest
14 ILO Classification report. Only interpretations by National Institute of
15 Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) certified "B" readers shall be
16 admissible.
17 2. Spirometric testing shall be conducted in accordance with the standards
18 recommended in the "Guides to the Evaluation of Permanent
19 Impairment" and the 1978 ATS epidemiology standardization project
20 with the exception that the predicted normal values for lung function
21 shall not be adjusted based upon the race of the subject. The FVC or the
22 FEV1 values shall represent the largest of such values obtained from
23 three (3) acceptable forced expiratory volume maneuvers as corrected to
24 BTPS (body temperature, ambient pressure and saturated with water
25 vapor at these conditions) and the variance between the two (2) largest
26 acceptable FVC values shall be either less than five percent (5%) of the
27 largest FVC value or less than one hundred (100) milliliters, whichever
Page 10 of 17
SB004710.100 - 984 - XXXX 2/19/2026 11:42 AM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 47/GA
1 is greater. The variance between the two (2) largest acceptable FEV1
2 values shall be either less than five percent (5%) of the largest FEV1
3 value or less than one hundred (100) milliliters, whichever is greater.
4 Reports of spirometric testing shall include a description by the
5 physician of the procedures utilized in conducting such spirometric
6 testing and a copy of the spirometric chart and tracings from which
7 spirometric values submitted as evidence were taken. If it is shown that
8 the spirometric testing is not valid due to inadequate cooperation or poor
9 effort on the part of the claimant, the claimant's right to take or
10 prosecute any proceedings under this chapter shall be suspended until
11 the refusal or obstruction ceases. No compensation shall be payable for
12 the period during which the refusal or obstruction continues.
13 3. The commissioner shall promulgate administrative regulations pursuant
14 to KRS Chapter 13A as necessary to effectuate the purposes of this
15 section. The commissioner shall periodically review the applicability of
16 the spirometric test values contained in the "Guides to the Evaluation of
17 Permanent Impairment" and may by administrative regulation substitute
18 other spirometric test values which are found to be more closely
19 representative of the normal pulmonary function of the coal mining
20 population.
21 4. The procedure for determination of occupational disease claims shall be
22 as follows:
23 a. Immediately upon receipt of an application for resolution of claim,
24 the commissioner shall notify the responsible employer and all
25 other interested parties and shall furnish them with a full and
26 complete copy of the application.
27 b. The commissioner shall assign the claim to an administrative law
