11 (4) (a) The right to compensation under this chapter resulting from an occupational
12 disease shall be forever barred unless a claim is filed with the commissioner
13 within three (3) years after the last injurious exposure to the occupational
14 hazard or after the employee first experiences a distinct manifestation of an
15 occupational disease in the form of symptoms reasonably sufficient to apprise
16 the employee that he or she has contracted the disease, whichever shall last
17 occur; and if death results from the occupational disease within that period,
18 unless a claim therefor be filed with the commissioner within three (3) years
19 after the death; but that notice of claim shall be deemed waived in case of
20 disability or death where the employer, or its insurance carrier, voluntarily
21 makes payment therefor, or if the incurrence of the disease or the death of the
22 employee and its cause was known to the employer. However, the right to
23 compensation for any occupational disease shall be forever barred, unless a
24 claim is filed with the commissioner within five (5) years from the last
25 injurious exposure to the occupational hazard, except that, in cases of
26 radiation disease, asbestos-related disease, or a type of cancer specified in
27 KRS 61.315(12)[(11)](b), a claim must be filed within twenty (20) years from
